To anyone who may read this.
My name is Mykos. I came from a town far away. After my father died, I was orphaned by our Temple of the Holy Twelve. There I grew up. I became an altar boy.
Once, we had a traveler coming to the Temple, in the midst of the night. He was badly wounded, and I was the only one on the watch. The man was in fever, he kept talking about a treasure he found and hid in distant lands. And a curse surrounding it. There was something morbidly enthralling about everything he was saying. I was consumed by this feeling. I wanted the fortunes he was talking about. I wanted it all. When our priest came into the hall, the man was already dead.
But his story was alive in me. It just wouldn't release its grip from me. I told no one. It took me a month to prepare for the journey. And then I left, covered by night. I traveled for five long years. I was looking for this place, a delirious chimera of a dying man.
And must be, I was cursed so deeply, that I did find it. First, I and my three fellows, as crooked and greedy as I am, arrived at a most lovely lake, near a small town called Grimstone. From there, along a small river I went, until I have found a shrine. THE shrine the dying traveler was telling me about. I tried to stay calm and reasonable, but couldn't help myself from laughing and crying. I did it. I found it. Untouched. I arrived here first. It took us four some days to figure out how to open the shrine. The key was in rotating the skulls in a right direction. They should all look at (erased).
Now it all means nothing. What a truly terrible things hides this cursed place. It was my punishment. It was my penalty. For my sins. For my biggest sin. I have to have this last confession.
It was I. That terrible night. When that man was lying on the floor, in my hands, and I heard the footsteps of the high priest. I was so scared. I was afraid, someone else will know about my treasure. I did it. I killed the man. I choked him, trying to not hear him rattling. I'm hearing it every night since. I killed a man under the roof of the Holy Temple.
Forgive me, Holy Father. I'm so sorry. I'm so sorry.
